 the ribs of testimony. You approach the Aeric Aerie with papers in hand and patience in your breath, and every step becomes a public argument made in calm ink rather than heated voice.\", \"outcome\": \"The writ makes later disputes dissolve like mist under noon, because cruel tongues cannot so easily claim you trespassed where you should not have walked. Your upward climb is slowed by the pageantry of signatures and the ritual of seals, but the Moonshard Lantern still drinks the three-note braid before the wind shifts and your timing remains sound. High Cantor Ysil Aer publicly praises your insistence on lawful rites, and the Vigil notes your cooperation in their ledger with a token that eases future crossings at night. The River Lords’ gossip machine tries to spin your paperwork into proof of guilt seeking cover, but the presence of the Oathwater Basin’s keeper at the initial stamping undercuts that angle. You find that one horn-log seal bears a fingernail burr that is not your own, proof that someone handled the wax after consecration, and the Spinegate scribe quietly pockets a copy of your note about it for later leverage. The law’s slow pace costs you nothing essential today, and it gains you a trail of names that may matter when the wrong note demands a voice in council.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"C4\", \"title\": \"Slip through the locked bone-song tube at night to feel the organ’s voice from within the cliff.\", \"text\": \"You wait for the lanterns along the ribwalk to thin into private constellations, and you move like a coal under ash toward the Temple’s secret tube that carries bone-song into the Aerie. The lock’s hiss is not disobedience but an older permission, because you carry the Breathkeepers’ token and a paladin’s oath that knows when rules are fences and when they are walls. Within, the stone is cool and the sound is not heard so much as worn like a garment, and you feel where the three notes scrape at your bones as if asking to be let out. You pla